West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name mainly from Woodthorpe in Strubby (Lincs), though occasionally from Woodthorpe in Loughborough (Leics). There is no evidence to suggest that the surname could be from other like-named places, such as Woodthorpe, Woodthorpe in Staveley (Derbys), Woodthorpe Hall in Handsworth, or Woodthorpe in Sandal Magna (WR Yorks), except perhaps for the early bearer from 1251–2."],"variants":[]},{"name":"THOMAS","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":28,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":37,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When THOMAS DE WOODTHORPE was born about 1187, in Saleby, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, ALAN DE WOODTHORPE, was 8 and his mother, Beatrice Farforth, was 28. He married